The function works as intended in this case. It correctly identifies that all elements in the input list are duplicates and returns a list containing the duplicate element.

If you want the function to return a list of all elements that appear more than once in the input list (i.e., all duplicates), you can modify the function to use a dictionary instead of a set to keep track of the counts of each element. Here's an example of how you can modify the function to achieve this:

```python
def find_duplicates(lst):
    seen = {}
    dupes = []
    for item in lst:
        if item in seen:
            seen[item] += 1
        else:
